4. LITERALS ➖
—-----------------------
Data or information giving to the java code
There are 4 types of literals
			1.  NUMBER
					1.INTEGER
					2.DECIMAL
			2. CHARACTER
			3. STRING
			4. BOOLEAN

1.NUMBER ➖
—------------------
Whenever we are declaring the numbers we can declare it directly.
Ex:-
—--
	System.out.println(100);
	System.out.println(10.2);


2.CHARACTER ➖
—------------------------
Whenever we are declaring the characters we can declare inside the single quotes
Inside the single quotes only one character is allowed

Ex:-
—-----
//System.out.println(h);CTE
System.out.println('h');
System.out.println('1');
//System.out.println('10');//CTE


3.STRING ➖
—-----------------
String is group of characters
Whenever we are declaring the string we have to include double quotes
There is no limitations for string

Ex:-
—---
System.out.println("sheela420");
System.out.println("1731285");


4.BOOLEAN ➖
—-------------------
Boolean data is a predefined data
There are 2 types 
true
false
Ex:-
—--\
System.out.println(true);
System.out.println(false);
